re the days. Horror movies aren&#039;t my jam, and neither are haunted houses, but people still need to get their kicks, and in Tokyo, that means a visit to Kowagarasetai, a Japanese haunted house and horror event production company. Roughly translated, Kowagarasetai means &#039;the Scaredy Squad&#039;. They claim the concept is the first of its kind, according to MSN: &quot;With the virus, I knew there would be no way we could have a traditional haunted house, with all that screaming in a small confined space,&quot; Kenta Iwana, Kowagarasetai&#039;s founder, said... &quot;When I read that drive-through theaters were making a comeback, it was my &#039;aha&#039; moment.&quot; Great, now I have a-ha&#039;s &#039;Take On Me&#039; stuck in my head, and so do you. The haunted house is located in a covered parking garage in downtown Tokyo, and the experience of driving through is supposed to simulate what it would be like to be stuck in a car during a zombie outbreak. For an extra fee, those who don&#039;t have a car can rent one, and there&#039;s the option for an extra-bloody package, too. Let&#039;s see some footage from the house, and hear from Kenta: \ufeff The temptation to wind down a window and throat punch someone would be extreme. More on how it all works: Drivers receive a set of Bluetooth speakers and the spooky tale begins. &quot;Around these parts, there&#039;s a legend that the ghosts attack humans. Honk your horn three times if you want to hear more,&quot; says the voice from the speaker, in Japanese. For the next 17 minutes, blood-soaked ghouls and zombies press up against the windows and rock the car. Once you&#039;re done, the company will clean your car so that you don&#039;t get horrified looks on the highway. Reports suggest demand is high, and Kenta claims there is currently a waiting list of around 1 000 people. I guess you have to hand it to them for a successful COVID-19 pivot. [source:msn]","headline":"Tokyo Drive-In Haunted House Is The Stuff O